@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Home Page";
    Layout = "~/Views/Shared/_HomeLayout.cshtml";
}

<style>
    .home-background {
        background-image: url('../images/leaf_3.jpg');
        min-height: 100vh;
        padding: 50px 20px;
        display: flex;
        justify-content: center;
        align-items: flex-start;
    }

    .home-content {
        background-color: #c7dbbf;
        padding: 40px;
        border-radius: 20px;
        max-width: 1200px;
        width: 100%;
        box-shadow: 0 8px 24px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
        font-family: 'Segoe UI', Tahoma, Geneva, Verdana, sans-serif;
        line-height: 1.8;
        font-size: 17px;
        opacity: .9;
    }

        .home-content p {
            margin-bottom: 30px;
        }

        .home-content strong {
            font-size: 18px;
            color: #2e7d32;
        }

    .section-title {
        font-size: 22px;
        font-weight: bold;
        color: #00796b;
        margin-bottom: 10px;
        display: inline-block;
    }
</style>

<div class="home-background">
    <div class="home-content">

        <p>
            <span class="section-title">Green Energy Facts</span><br><br />
            1. <strong>Solar energy can already be cheaper than fossil fuels</strong><br />
            – in many countries, solar panels produce energy more cost-effectively than traditional sources.<br><br />
            2. <strong>A single wind turbine can power up to 1,500 homes</strong><br />
            – depending on location and size.<br><br />
            3. <strong>Green data centers are becoming more common</strong><br />
            – companies like Apple and Google now run data centers powered entirely by renewable energy.
        </p>

        <p>
            <span class="section-title">Data Warehouses and Energy Usage</span><br><br />
            1. <strong>Data warehouses consume a lot of energy due to continuous operation</strong><br />
            – storing and querying data generates heat and high workload.<br><br />
            2. <strong>Optimized queries = lower energy use</strong><br />
            – writing efficient SQL and using proper indexing not only speeds things up, but also reduces power consumption.<br><br />
            3. <strong>Accurate data types matter</strong><br />
            – using unnecessarily large types (like <code>VARCHAR(255)</code> instead of <code>VARCHAR(50)</code>) requires more memory and energy.
        </p>

        <p>
            <span class="section-title">Reducing Energy Use in Data Centers</span><br><br />
            1. <strong>Heat recovery</strong><br />
            – some data centers reuse the heat from servers to warm residential buildings.<br><br />
            2. <strong>Immersion cooling</strong><br />
            – servers are submerged in special liquids that conduct heat efficiently, reducing the need for traditional air conditioning.<br><br />
            3. <strong>AI for energy optimization</strong><br />
            – Google's AI systems, for example, can reduce cooling energy needs in real time by up to 40%.
        </p>

    </div>
</div>
